{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Form better relationships with other stakeholders involved in Open Scholarship developments (e.g., librarians, policymakers, publishers and other service providers, Open Access advocates, and those actively teaching, plus ICT and other support positions for science & education).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Work for, and collaborate with, researchers who practice various aspects of Open Scholarship, ranging from developing Open Source software and tools to posting preprints and citizen science, and sharing experiences made with approaches to open education.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Encourage the wider adoption of an open mindset that emphasises the importance of the research process over the outcome.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Sign the San Francisco Declaration on Research Assessment (DORA) as a commitment to improving how research is assessed. Make sure to adhere to the principles too in practice.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab As an alternative, adopt the Leiden Manifesto.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab For education, sign the Cape Town Open Education Declaration to commit to the pursuit of the Declaration\u8217's three strategies as a part of one\u8217's teaching, learning and/or work life.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab For those interested in doing more, makes sure to heed the Ten Directions to Move Open Education Forward.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Refuse to sign copyright transfer agreements, unless you are allowed to retain copyright of your work under a Creative Commons license of your own choosing.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 GROUP LEVEL (E.G., LABS, DEPARTMENTS)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Locate Open Scholarship hotspots (i.e., venues or groups for regular exchange and discussion about community building) and find a way to link them together to help community cohesion and expansion.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab If a local Open Scholarship hotspot does not yet exist, establish it (e.g., using the Meetup platform).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Use these national/international/regional communities to support lower-level learning and knowledge sharing of Open Scholarship practices, especially in varying cultural settings.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Start discussions towards an implicit or explicit (shared) open science pledge or code of conduct for your department, lab, or research group. This can be based on existing ones, such as the Contributor Covenant.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Establish rights experts who might help with questions regarding copyright issues and the effective use of Creative Commons licenses.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Highlight best practice showcases in order to demonstrate what is actually possible with Open Scholarship, and what the wider advantages can be.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Engage communication departments and research assessment officials. Organize sessions to tell them about open science and scholarship, and be sensitive to the fact that it may imply they change their entire view of what is important in science and what their role could be.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Adopt best practices for Open Scholarship, including shared data as a research output, addressing publication bias, and \u8220"questionable research practices\u8221" with bias-reducing workflows.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Advocate to decision makers at scholarly journals, publishers, funders, and higher education and research institutions to recognize and reward a variety of Open Scholarship activities, particularly regarding research evaluation and open education policies.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Start discussions with University Ranking Providers (e.g., QS, Times Higher Education) to include an openness element to their indicators.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Initiate debates on meaningful standards and practices at a disciplinary level for publishing data (e.g., the FAIR principles).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Improve engagement between faculty advisory boards, researchers, students and librarians regarding Open Scholarship practices (see Fig. 1 and 2) and principles.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Refuse to engage with publishers who have restrictive preprint, Open Access, and copyright policies.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 INSTITUTE LEVEL (INCLUDING RESEARCH AND FUNDING BODIES)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Research libraries should collect information about how the sector as a whole interacts with the research literature. Such information could be used to help with publisher negotiations, break up big deal contracts, and cancel subscriptions by providing evidence into the cross-sectorial value of services, and includes:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Which venues researchers are publishing in;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Who is doing the editorial and peer review work;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab How much is being spent on serial subscriptions;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab How much is being spent on Article Processing Charges (APCs) and Book Processing Charges (BPCs) for Open Access; and\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Which articles are being downloaded and cited.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Map and coordinate when current subscription and big deal licenses will run out across research institutes, and let it happen. Where cancellations or terminations occur, ensure that there is adequate post-subscription access and support using existing sustainable and legal mechanisms (e.g., Inter-Library Loan). Explore routes for reinvesting money saved for library budgets.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Purchase back any legacy documents and incorporate them into the scholarly body of work. Also improve the open sharing and archiving of legacy articles on which copyright has expired.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Help to inform researchers more about the Author Alliance termination of transfer tool to help them retain their rights as authors.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Research funders can define the limits of what is an acceptable standard of publication. They therefore have the power to mandate publication in journals with a cap on APCs and BPCs, or in OA-only venues (with specific licenses), or in those with short or zero-length embargoes on self-archiving (e.g., Emerald, The Royal Society).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Refuse to engage with publishers that double dip on payments, and demand transparency and data in cases where there is a suspicion that this is occurring (for an overview, see e.g.\u160?Buranyi, 2017).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Refuse to engage with publishers in which there is no transparency around pricing for either subscriptions or Open Access. This includes with publishers who insist on using non-disclosure agreements as part of licensing contract terms.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Engage publishers on being more transparent about the financial aspects of their publishing workflows, similar to those such as Ubiquity Press.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Insist that publishers make all bibliographic records, usage metrics, and citation data freely available and accessible in both a human- and machine-readable format.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Develop rights retention policies for scholarly research at research institutes that currently lack them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Adopt the CASRAI CRediT (Contributor Rules Taxonomy) guidelines to help identify author contributions more clearly.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Refuse to engage with publishers who have restrictive preprint, Open Access, and copyright policies.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Encourage further adoption by publishers of the Initiative for Open Citations (I4OC) in conjunction with the wider uptake of open standards.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab For research institutes that currently lack them, either launch and maintain an Open Access repository or find an existing resource to use, and adopt an Open Access policy. Make these easily discoverable and accessible on the institutional website, and any relevant indexing services.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Examples of Open Access policies can be found e.g.\u160?via the ROARMAP\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Examples of Open Education / OER policies are listed in e.g.\u160?the Creative Commons OER policy registry, or the European Union\u8217's Policy approaches to Open Education, 2017.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Promote and compensate time and effort spent on training and advocacy for the various aspects of Open Scholarship, including Open Source, Open Access, and Open Education.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Enable and foster local support structures such as openlabs and open publication and research learning, guidance and advice offers.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Engage with research communities to develop and advertise quantifiable incentives for sharing preprints, open data, reproducible analyses, and OA in hiring, promotion, and tenure decisions. Define new ways of describing these wider contributions to scientific communities.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Encourage and adopt the principles for fairer research assessment outlined in DORA. Make sure that those in charge of research assessment, including hiring, tenure, and grant-awarding committees adhere to these.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Explore substituting proprietary software with open source alternatives.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Require researchers to work with open standards and file formats (either exclusively or in addition to proprietary standards and file formats).\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 NATIONAL LEVEL (OR HIGHER)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Create new or support/contact existing international library consortia/collaborations (e.g., the International Coalition of Library Consortia) to co-operate on infrastructure developments (e.g., LIBER, EIFL, ARL, and SPARC).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Sign on to the Global Sustainability Coalition for Open Science Services (SCOSS), and investigate coalitions with the Open Research Funders Group.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Consortia like the German Projekt DEAL could provide examples of how to take the first step towards this at a national level. Gaining support from SPARC for any such developments would also be useful.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Build on faculty and funder support for Open Access and related quality assurance initiatives (e.g., peer review) that are decoupled from journals. Agree on, and develop, a governance structure for a world-wide scholarly infrastructure (e.g., W3C).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Create scholarly standards to implement an alternative non-profit and community-owned scholarly publishing platform/environment (using the funds freed from subscriptions, building on existing repositories/environments and infrastructure).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Support collaborations such as Metadata 2020, NISO/NIST, and eLife, to help build a richer connectivity between scholarly communication systems and communities.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Take action against the privatisation of scholarly works and processes in order to achieve transformation of the publishing industry into one comprised of fair licensing, fair market competition, and under the ownership of the scholarly community.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Create a cost-effectiveness analysis of Open Scholarship (e.g., true cost of article publishing) to be used as the basis for an argument about how much taxpayer money it costs every year to delay decisions in the above areas.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Implement currently available sort, filter and search/discovery technology across scholarship outputs.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Enable unrestricted text and data mining over this content.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Research funders and libraries hold most of the purse strings, and further engagement on this front is essential, especially in defining their relative roles in developing or funding scholarly infrastructure. Simply channelling more money into the existing system, with perverse incentives and skewed power dynamics, is clearly no longer sustainable for research.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Develop sustainable, regional and national roadmaps for Open Scholarship.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Encourage research funders to diversify the portfolio of what is considered as a research output for assessment purposes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Wider adoption of preprint and Open Access policies similar to those at the NIH (USA) and Wellcome Trust (UK).\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Encourage research funders to develop calls to support evidence- and theory-based interventions to promote Open Scholarship.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Fund determinant studies that use behavior change theory to map the determinants of engaging in different Open Scholarship practices (e.g., why do some researchers routinely publish preprints while others do not? Are the arguments produced by researchers opposed to data sharing indeed the reasons why those who do not share data, do not?)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Fund studies that use stakeholder theory to explore ways to achieve more Open Scholarship policies at research and education institutions.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab A reduction of article-processing charges (APCs) in hybrid titles to match the market average for OA-only journals.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab A reduction of article-processing charges (APCs) and book-processing charges (BPCs) in hybrid titles to match the market average for OA-only journals and presses.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab The scholarly publishing market might require a detailed government-level investigation in order to stabilise this.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Mandate ORCID for researchers across all research outputs to help assist in the persistent identification of authors across the entire research literature, and easier research discoverability.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Where subscriptions have not yet expired, mandate offsetting agreements for hybrid journal titles in order to reduce double-dipping.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Where offsetting deals are in place, these can be streamlined and standardised across sectors to reduce administrative burden.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab For scholarly publishers to engage with the new UK Scholarly Communications License that enables authors to retain more of their rights. This would reduce the time spent on embargo processing, the cost spent on hybrid APCs and BPCs, and for researchers in the UK, help them to comply with the UKRI Open Access policy.\par}
